Question 1:

Use read.csv to load in “HW12-TVsales.dat”, calling it SALES. A cable home shopping network wants to study the relationship the number of items purchased by customers (soldunits) based on its price (saleprice), promotions (discount and shipdiscount), number of viewers (viewers), and time of year (weektype and week). They feel that the number of shows devoted to the product per week (shows), total amount of time it was shown on TV (duration), and the products novelty (novelty, a score given by focus groups that rates how new and interesting the product is to consumers) also influence sales.

SALES <- read.csv("HW12-TVsales.dat")  #uncomment and run code

a. Fit a simple linear regression where \(y\) is soldunits and \(x\) is saleprice and run check.regression (with the additional argument tests=FALSE) and visualize.model. Like many relationships in business analytics, there is a large amount of heteroscedasticity and a regression in the original variables is a bad idea. A further issue here is that the regression is unaware that the quantity sold has to be positive (but 95% prediction intervals include many negative values). We need to “fix” the data before modeling. No response to write here, just R code.

#Fit simple linear regression
Selling <- lm(soldunits~saleprice, data = SALES)
#Visualize model
visualize.model(Selling)

#check.regression  (with extra argument tests=FALSE)
check.regression(Selling,tests=FALSE)

#.165

b. Perhaps a better \(y\) variable would be the number of items sold per viewer since we “know” that with more people watching, more items should be sold (the company can’t directly choose a value of viewership anyway). Make a scatterplot of the quantity soldunits/viewers versus saleprice to see that this is STILL not an appropriate relationship to model with a regression. Note: you can do this with plot by specifying soldunits/viewers ~ saleprice as the formula you are plotting. As with most scatterplots, you will need the data= argument as well. No response to write here, just R code.

#Scatterplot code 
plot(soldunits/viewers~saleprice,data=SALES)

c. Modeling the logarithms of quantities often allows regression to be an appropriate model. The following code will add a variable called y to the dataframe defined as the log10 of soldunits/viewers and deletes the original columns. It then replaces the original values of shows, duration, saleprice, and novelty with their logarithms. You will be predicting y from these variables for the remainder of this question. Make a scatterplot of this \(y\) variable versus saleprice (which is now the log10 of the original sale price) to see that the regression may now be a reasonable model. No response to write here, just R code.

#Uncomment the following lines and run them (you still need to write the code for plot)
SALES$y <- log10(SALES$soldunits/SALES$viewers)
SALES$soldunits <- NULL
SALES$viewers <- NULL
SALES$shows <- log10(SALES$shows)
SALES$duration <- log10(SALES$duration)
SALES$saleprice <- log10(SALES$saleprice)
SALES$novelty <- log10(SALES$novelty)

#Scatterplot of y vs. saleprice
plot(y~saleprice,data=SALES)

d. We are now ready to build a predictive model. Split the data into 65% training and 35% holdout. Be sure to set.seed(320) immediately before the sample command. No response to write here, just R code.

#set seed
set.seed(320)
#determine rows for training set
train.rows <- sample(1:nrow(SALES),0.65*nrow(SALES))
TRAIN <- SALES[train.rows,]
HOLDOUT <- SALES[-train.rows,]

e. Let us consider regression model. At this point, you could run build.model on TRAIN to find a model with a reasonably small estimated generalization error. This takes a while (so don’t do it), but the result is a model with the formula y~saleprice*(discount+novelty)+duration*novelty+week. Use the code below to fit this model on TRAIN, then determine its RMSE on the holdout sample. Run see.interactions (with argument cex=0.5 to make legends small). Discuss when the relationship between \(y\) and discount is positive vs. negative and when the relationship is relatively strong vs. relatively weak.

M <- lm(y~saleprice*(discount+novelty)+duration*novelty+week,data=TRAIN)  #Uncomment and run
